textOriginal:
I am Moroccan 🇲🇦 and we have a similar method called عملية (“ Amaliya”) which means operation but that’s actually also known as the wrap technique. 
You take small strand of hair and wrap it around your whole  head, you fix the stand with pins and you repeat the process until the whole head is wrapped. Your hair has toe be damped while doing it then you put a scarf on your head and sleep with it. The next morning your hair are stretched for coily hair and straightened for curly to wavy hair. 
We also use kardoune like Algerian. 
My mom did عملية during her whole teenage and early adulthood. 
It really works for all types of hair 👍🏼

textOriginal:
Hard question, I would say c) bc…
Why I pickled c) moisturiser
For a) mascara I can live without, I can curl my lashes, if that doesn’t count I will use products to make them longer so I don’t need mascara 
For b) I can use lip balm bc lip balm and lip gloss are to diffrent things, lip balm is something that helps your lips stay smooth and healthy, lip gloss is when you put on a product in your lip to make it glossy/shiny
For d) if I can’t use perfume I will use moisturiser that’s strong and smells great, also I would use body mist, body mist is very similar to perfume but it’s not the same, body mist is a lot lighter in strength than perfume, perfume is a lot heavier and uses less for a strong smell if u were to use body mist you would have to use a lot more product for a strong smell
Why I choose C) moisturiser 
There’s so many things you can use for moisturiser and so many types of moisturiser, for skin,lips and face for ex.
Moisturiser can keep my skin from being dry, none of the others can. Moisturiser also keeps my skin and other stuff healthy and smooth also fresh.
Besides moisturiser if I had to pick something else it would be D) perfume 
As I said I can live without a) and b) I use moisturiser for many reasons that I listed, I also use it to smell better, so perfume would be the next best thing to make me smell good. Mascara doesn’t make me smell good ofc, it just makes my lashes longer. Lip gloss also doesn’t make me smell good ofc, ik some lipglosses are scented, but it doesn’t make my whole body smell splendid, so that’s why if I couldn’t choose moisturiser it would be perfume 

Hopefully my reasons are good enough, and you get what I mean. That’s it for now I might add more but not likely.

textOriginal:
OMFG I can't believe people say such things... spoiler alert: If you color your hair, your regrowth almost always looks darker and softer in color than it would if you had your virgin hair all over your head and it had actually seen the sun each year for several years straight. Hair lightens and brightens in the sun. The longer the hair the more lightness and warmth will be visible throughout the lengths. That's how stylists came to the idea of creating the lived in balayage hair colors which are supposed to mimic that phenomenon. If you're a lighter blonde naturally, your hair will probably grow out from your scalp looking a bit mousy or even "boring" a dusty color, if you will. But it will reveal the underlying pigments the further it grows out and shine in its true beauty, really. That's also how naturally red hair often times looks more vibrant in the lengths and a bit softer in the regrowth. Or how dark hair might look a bit dull in the very roots but nicely bronzy in the lengths. I thought this was common sense, sorry for being that naive... 
e.g. my hair looked like a mousy brown when I buzzed it all off and it grew out, but it can turn into a honey/caramel blonde naturally without adding chemicals, bleach, dye, whatever. You should try it, you might be surprized about the beauty that lies beneath the top layer of eumelanin. And maybe this will save you some money and lots of damage... just an idea. Of course if you got super short hair and keep it that short, you might never figure it out anyways, that's a different story.

textOriginal: White blonde is crazy to deal with tbh, i grew out of the color as I got older so a lot of the quirks are there but much much less strong. My hair is still super low porosity and struggles to take color. When I had natural platinum hair tho it was SOOO hair dye resistant which is WILD because it had no natural pigment. I had to re-dye my hair every 12 DAYS with manic panic semipermanent ultraviolet to keep it fresh because it would start fading by day 4-6. I was only shampooing it twice a week max (for color conservation and naturally not oily). I bleached it once to see if it would make the dye last longer. It did, i had to grow out and cut it off, but also 1 round of 20 vol for 20 mins with no toner & pre and post treatment fried my hair SO badly i had to go shampoo free for two years to keep ot healthy or it would feel and behave like a broom. It was pretty but so inconvenient so im appreciating the lower maintenance changes my hair has gone through as I've aged.
title: ONLY way I’ve seen my natural hair color look bright, vibrant, and light is by taking care of it!

textOriginal:
Absolutely not! Taking care of their skin is very important for teenagers, and it goes beyond just focusing on their studies. When they pay attention to their skincare, it not only benefits their overall health but also boosts their self-esteem. Good skincare habits help keep their skin healthy, which can enhance their confidence.

If teenagers neglect their skincare, they may face various skin problems, such as acne, pimples, or oily skin. These issues can affect their self-image, which in turn can impact their studies and social interactions.

Therefore, it is essential for them to incorporate some basic skincare habits into their routine, such as:

1. Drinking water: Staying hydrated is crucial for skin health. Drinking enough water helps keep the skin fresh and glowing.

2. Washing their face: They should wash their face twice a day to remove dirt and oil.

3. Applying sunscreen: Using sunscreen is important to protect the skin from the sun's harmful UV rays, preventing skin damage.

4. Eating a healthy diet: Consuming fruits and vegetables is beneficial for skin health. A diet rich in vitamins and minerals nourishes the skin.

5. Getting adequate sleep: Good sleep is also essential for skin health. Lack of sleep can lead to dark circles and dull skin.

These habits are not only good for the skin but also beneficial for overall health. Therefore, teenagers should understand the importance of taking care of themselves so they can maintain their health and beauty while managing their studies. Finding a balance is key.

textOriginal: @@suyung58 Hi, Susan.  Yes, there are some brands that are less likely to irritate eyes. textOriginal: As someone that meets conventionally attractive standards and does not look good in dramatic makeup—it makes me look like a child playing with her mother’s makeup—the concept of “no makeup is always better” often but not always comes from a place of pretty privilege. I prefer light makeup, not none when I have the time with an outfit I put a lot of thought into. Sure vanity isn’t always the best, but making myself feel presentable based on my standards really makes my seem better. Basically, no makeup makes you feel your best? Awesome! Dramatic looks? Super cool! Light makeup? Also fine! Take care of your skin, of course, but using mineral water/oil cleanser followed with a water-soluble cleaner and daily SPF will ensure to minimize any negative impacts. Also, test products to see hope your skin reacts!

textOriginal:
I understand the girl in the audio is pick me, but what she said about the ingredients in makeup ruining your skin is actually spot on. Your skin is an ORGAN, it absorbs not just the skincare you put on it but anything you put on it. Makeup does lead to skin irritation, inflammation, bad skin, etc. the context in which this girl in the audio said all this was not the best, but what she said was not wrong. 
 
Lowkey makes me happy that we can’t access any of our other organs tbh, because God knows what we would end up putting on them 😂

All that is to say, I actually do wear makeup on occasion, although recently I’ve been trying to go fully bare faced and the difference I’ve seen in my skin in only a week has been insane. 

I don’t think it has anything to do with beauty or whatever, the only thing is, if you’re making a choice, make sure it’s an informed choice, make sure you know what’s in your products ♥️
